text: This is actually happening. They are ACTUALLY doing this.   The first film was, admittedly, not all that great. Blue Tones, Even to Long Padding, and a moderately scary final Kill Scene ending on the implication that it could continue on forever.   The Second Film? I kind of hoped it'd be the final one, and it was helped by having a stronger emotional tone than the first film. Even though it made less of its money back than its' predecessor, I'd still remember the film's story and intentions fondly. Mother wants to save her child from being assimilated by Creepy Oni Girl. Mother endeavors to find out everything about Creepy Long-haired Oni Girl, then uses that knowledge to "Defeat" Creepy Long-haired Girl. Probably.   Okay. Well.   .....   Maybe it was better to stop at just 2 films? Maybe don't make a 3rd one that might not even make HALF of what either of the two preceding films had barely managed to make on their opening weekends? Maybe the first two films were good- ..... Decent enough on their own that they DON'T need to have whatever little respect they had as actually good Horror Films be taken away through a 3rd Film defecating on their fame?  No? You want to go through with this project and barely manage a "3%" on Rotten Tomatoes, and thus end up with the film immediately sent back to the Internet as another obscure Viral Feed to exhibit to future Filmmakers and Scriptwriters how UNORIGINAL, and UNINSPIRED it was in its EXECUTION, PLOT, CHARACTERS, EDITING, PACING, and ACTING??!?  You are truly fascinating, you lot are. No, I mean it. Really. You are utterly fascinating in how devoid of originality and how desperate you are and shallow. Maybe I might be going too far. But I say "Shallow" solely because of that Gothy looking girl at the beginning of the trailer. I can tell she has not been in acting school for very long. Hope your little movie's acting talent isn't entirely like that. Or maybe it is, and it proves my point.  The point being that this movie is a bird who's wings have already been clipped and will never soar.

text: You know what was great about the original? I'm not talking about the Naomi Watts crap film, I mean the original Japanese film that was actually based off the book. It was that through out the whole film you weren't entirely sure if it was real or not. The tone and the subtlety is what made it creepy but if you weren't aware of the ending or the American remakes you would question if what was happening was real or if it was just a myth. It was so well done and didn't rely on overused horror cliches like the American remake. I haven't seen this film yet so I'm not including it entirely here but the Naomi Watts ones weren't very good at all. People always say how scary it was and how they watched it as a kid. Kids are stupid, of course you found it scary then. But the idea of it almost seeming like it wasn't real is what made it more terrifying at the end when the reveal happens. Also, in regards to subtlety. I've always hated the western design of the little girl. Fucking hell, she looks like she's wearing bad Halloween make up in the older films and this one included. Uncanny valley is scary, these films just go for monster movie make up. The original films just had her in a clean white gown and her face was barely shown at all because seeing it made it less scary. By the way, I love Naomi Watts as an actor, but those films were just awful.
